helpe fitte for mee, which hath part of

But in the exposition of the fifth com
maundment we perceived how much
God doth set by the love and goodwill
of children to their parentes, and what
a charge he giveth to children to ho
nour them. It must needes be there
fore that wedlocke is a most heavenly
ordinaunce, since it is preferred be
fore the honouring of parentes: and
yet neverthelesse it is so preferred, as
that by the law of matrimonie, the
precept for the honour due to parents
may not be abolished, but that there
by married folkes may knowe to be
have themselves so, if their parentes
goe about to breede discorde betwixt
them and their spouses, that then they
suffer not themselmes for their pa
rentes wordes to be severed, but in
all things else to honour them as they

This nowe (saith he) is bone of my bones, and flesh of my flesh. I have found (saith he) I have found an helpe fitte for mee, which hath part of my flesh, of my bloud, and my verie substance. From hence riseth and yet remayneth that naturall pronenesse of men toward woman: when on the otherside overthwart mingling and medling of cursed men with beastes contrarie to mans nature was long agoe destroyed by fire, which shewed that God did abhore it. The Lorde moreover sayde: A man shall forsake his father and his mother, and cleave to his wife, and two shall be one flesh But in the exposition of the fifth com maundment we perceived how much God doth set by the love and goodwill of children to their parentes, and what a charge he giveth to children to ho nour them. It must needes be there fore that wedlocke is a most heavenly ordinaunce, since it is preferred be fore the honouring of parentes: and yet neverthelesse it is so preferred, as that by the law of matrimonie, the precept for the honour due to parents may not be abolished, but that there by married folkes may knowe to be have themselves so, if their parentes goe about to breede discorde betwixt them and their spouses, that then they suffer not themselmes for their pa rentes wordes to be severed, but in all things else to honour them as they should. The holy Patriarches kept
the lawe of matrimonie, and reveren
ced wedlocke verie devoutely. For no
small parcell of the first and most ex
cellent booke of the Bible called Ge
nesis, is spent in rehearsing the mar
riages of holie men. Neyther is Mo
ses the peerelesse servant of God a
shamed to make mention of the busi
nes and workes of wedlocke as pure
and excellent, which seeme to many
at this day to be foule and filthie.
Christ himselfe (who being the verie
naturall sonne of God, was himselfe
borne in wedlocke although of a pure
and uncorupted Virgine) did honour
and commend the knotte of matrimo
nie, while hee did vouchsafe to shewe
his first miracle at a wedding, which
was such a myracle as did declare
that the Lorde is able to make the bit
ternesse of marriage sweete, and the
scarcitie thereof to abound with plen
tie. As the Apostles were married
men according to the examples of the
patriarches, kinges, princes, priestes,
and prophetes: So Paul the chiefe of
all the Apostles, cryeth out and saith:
Wedlocke is honourable among all,
and the bedde undefiled. But whore
mongers and adulterers God will
judge. He sayeth taht wedlocke is ho
nourable among all, he meaneth, all
nations: For verie fewe people shall
you find that do not greatly commend
the state of marriage. Xenophon thin
keth taht among all Gods ordinaun
ces scant anie one can be found that is
more commendable or profitable than
wedlocke is. Musonius, Hierocles,
and other auncient sages thinke mar
riage to bee so necessarie to live well
and conveniently, that the life of man
without marriage seemeth to be may
med. Even they (ye heathens I meane)
doe make the evils and discommodi
ties of marriage to consist in ye married
